nd commenting emotionally on it. The letters of the alphabet are danced by the chorus, the cognitive and communicative power of gestures and body expression providing emotional context. A barking pickle brine from Thasos is perhaps an olfactory somatosensory visual and auditory embodiment of Archilochean poetry, whilst the actor’s foot in dance is a visual and motor embodiment of a metrical foot on stage. Comedy with its actors, costumes, masks, and props is overflowing with such examples. In this book, the author suggests that comedy made a significant contribution to the establishment of scholarly discourses in Classical Greece.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aGelehrtheit. 4aGriechenland (Altertum) / Antike. 4aGriechisch. 4aKomödie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Greek comedy.  aClassical Greece.  aearly Greek scholarship.  aenactivism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z97831111757820 cEPUBz97831110817620 cprintz978311108093240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311108154040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111081540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111081540/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK